    "narrative": "For April 30, the **Austin Waves** offense is anchored by **Gunnar Henderson**, who earns our highest efficiency score of 81.88. His matchup against McCullers Jr. (4.94 xERA) is the most favorable on the board, further amplified by a massive 16% park boost and a slow delivery from the opposing pitcher that creates an elite environment for his speed-based stolen base upside. Similarly, **Jacob Wilson** (71.63) presents a strong start at the top of the order; his 10% park factor and the matchup against the weaker Cameron (4.33 xERA) make him a foundational piece for today\u2019s production. While **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.** (67.95) faces a stiffer test against Ober, his high xwOBA and the 12% boost from a favorable pitcher profile solidify his position as a high-floor producer despite the dynamic platoon challenge.\n\nThe marginal start decision of the day revolves around **Nasim Nunez** (45.93) and **Coby Mayo** (43.05). **Nasim Nunez** earns the nod specifically for our emphasis on stolen base scarcity; despite a 4% park penalty, the 92% SB-success probability against the opposing battery keeps him ahead of other bench options. **Coby Mayo** represents a high-variance play; while his 16% park boost is significant, his low lineup position and the skill level of Lambert result in a capped ceiling. With **Kyle Tucker**, **Luis Robert Jr.**, **Jackson Merrill**, and **Andy Pages** all unavailable due to off-days or injury, the current depth chart remains static. We are monitoring **Drake Baldwin** (53.50) closely, as his status relies on the confirmed lineup; should he drop out of the #2 spot, we may see his efficiency score dip further toward the 40-point threshold, forcing a re-evaluation of our bench depth featuring **Jordan Westburg** or **Jorge Polanco**. \n\nRisk management remains a priority given the SP strength faced by some of our middle-infield options. While **Luis Garc\u00eda Jr.** (59.83) boasts a solid 14% platoon edge against Peralta, the overall strength of that matchup keeps him just shy of our \"Strong\" tier. We are avoiding the temptation to rotate in players like **Josh Lowe**, **Marcell Ozuna**, or **Miguel Vargas** until we see positive shifts in park factors or opposing pitcher profiles. As we look ahead, we continue to track the development of **Josh Jung**, **Nolan Schanuel**, **Brady House**, **Dominic Smith**, and **Liam Hicks** on the bench, waiting for a breakout in their individual ATC projections to justify displacing the current starters.",
